{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01H2vJkxS4dy5sS7GpL3HVYe","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"All three jobs completed successfully. Here's the comparison summary:\n\n## Results Summary\n\n| Strategy | Elapsed (job log) | Technique | Outcome |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Baseline** | 25.58s | Shuffle join (no optimization) | 44x skew ratio — max partition 11,579 rows vs min 263 |\n| **Broadcast Join** | 14.3s | Broadcasts small `products` table to all workers | No shuffle, no skew — **~44% faster** |\n| **AQE** | 14.2s | Adaptive Query Execution auto-splits hot partitions | Auto-detects skew at runtime — **~45% faster** |\n\n**Key findings:**\n- The baseline suffered a **44x skew ratio** (5 hot products getting 50% of orders created partitions 44× larger than average), causing straggler tasks.\n- **Broadcast join** eliminates the skew entirely by avoiding the shuffle — the small `products` table is replicated to each executor so no partitioning on `product_id` occurs.\n- **AQE** (`spark.sql.adaptive.skewJoin.enabled=true`) detects hot partitions at runtime and automatically splits them, achieving nearly the same speedup without requiring knowledge of table sizes upfront.\n\nBoth optimization strategies satisfy the success criteria — baseline completed showing skew, and both broadcast and AQE jobs completed successfully."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":171,"cache_read_input_tokens":31911,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":171},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"d8b22c5a-5580-4256-8558-4682258c177b","uuid":"2aafd2fb-de43-4151-ac26-f90fb86b432e","request_id":"req_011CcgTsZnkW5smWwRUpTmW3"}
